<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-302-764  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 302 764.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 2 1990 v7 n13 p116(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Judge throws out five of six charges in Xerox interface suit.andO;(Xerox Corp. lawsuit against Apple Computer Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doler, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. (cases)Apple Computer Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; XRX.andO;Topic:     Legal IssuesCopyrightSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Kathleen DolerandM;Xerox Corp.'s effort to sue Apple Computer Inc. over the Macintosh graphicalinterface suffered a setback in San Francisco recently after a federal judgedismissed all but one of Xerox's charges.andM;Judge Vaughn Walker has thrown out five of the six charges that were filedagainst Apple in December, including Xerox's claim that Apple unfairlybenefited from selling a graphical interface invented by Xerox.andM;Xerox plans to appeal the decision.andM;The only remaining charge seeks a declaratory judgment confirming Xerox'sclaims to ownership of the 1980 Star software copyright.andM;According to legal experts, Xerox was hurt by its unusual approach to thelawsuit.andP;  Ronald Laurie, a computer law attorney with Irell andamp; Manella ofMenlo Park, Calif., said Xerox never brought a copyright infringement suitagainst Apple, but instead claimed unfair competition.andP;  However, copyrightstatutes state that suits over copyrights cannot claim unfair competition,said Laurie.andM;&quot;All of the lawyers [observing the suit] were wondering why in the worldXerox didn't allege copyright infringement,&quot; he said.andM;Xerox asked the court to cancel Apple's Macintosh copyrights on the groundsthat the interface technology was developed by Xerox in the late 1970s.andP;  ButJudge Walker threw out these allegations because Xerox had not claimedcopyright infringement.andO;</TEXT></DOC>